|-ASTER OPERATING SYSTEM INSTALLATION--------------------------------JULY 2026-|

    To compile the operating system, run the <build.sh> script in the <etc>
directory with the "-b" argument. If the script fails, you likely are missing a
dependency. Please see the BUILD SYSTEM DEPENDENCIES section below. A disk image
will be produced that can be used via all the normal manners of installing an
operating system to hardware or a VM. If it doesn't compile on your system, open
a ticket upstream in the code repository.

    To see all possible build arguments, use the "-h" switch when running the
build script.

|-ASTER BUILD SYSTEM DEPENDENCIES------------------------------------JULY 2026-|

    The build system does require some external tools to be present on your
system, and you should ensure you have the required tools before you run the
script, lest you waste time.

- POSIX sh: A POSIX-compatible shell is required to run the build script itself.
  More featureful shells like Bash or Dash SHOULD work, but are not guaranteed
  and will not be compromised for if it derails the script somehow.
- NASM: A NASM-compatible assembler is required to compile things like the
  bootloader and bootstrap DSL compiler.

|-ASTER OPERATING SYSTEM DEPENDENCIES--------------------------------JULY 2026-|

    Aster requires quite a few things to be bootable on your hardware (and may
still fail if all these conditions are met);

- ALL MODES
  - An x86_64 processor. This may also be referred to as AMD64.
  - A BIOS or UEFI-capable motherboard. Nearly all motherboards ever
    manufactured should have at least a BIOS (sometimes referred to as Legacy
    Boot).
- BIOS MODE
  - ACPI-compliance without serious bugs or imperfections, usually contained in
    BIOSes after January 1st, 2001.
  - VESA/DDC-compliance of recommended version 2Ab.
  - VESA/VBE-compliance of at least version 2.0.
  - Support for the INT 15, AX=E820 memory mapping interrupt. This nearly always
    accompanies any BIOS after 2002.
- UEFI MODE
  - Not supported yet!

    NOTE: Aster is experimental! While at a very small chance, it may damage
your system on boot attempt. Into the forseeable future, booting in a virtual
machine is always the reccommended approach.

